<?xml version="1.0"?><collection name="D0841-A"><document name="APW_ENG_20050407.0086"><line>California, Hawaii and New Jersey also allow for domestic partnerships _ though California and Hawaii also have states laws that define marriage as between a man and a woman.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="4" sums="12,42,43,5"><scu uid="52" label="New Jersey took steps toward allowing gay marriage" weight="1"/><scu uid="53" label="Hawaii took steps toward allowing gay marriage" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041001.0493"><line>A country-by-country review of current legislation:</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041109.0231"><line>This is a happy case,&quot; Zappone declared outside the High Court, Ireland's second-highest court.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050407.0086"><line>Kansans voted by a more than 2-to-1 margin Tuesday to ban gay marriages and civil unions, and voters also ousted the lone gay city council member in Topeka, Tiffany Muller, who had defeated an emphatically anti-gay opponent in the primary.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041105.0605"><line>Citing legal precedents elsewhere in Canada, the Saskatchewan court ruled the Canadian law limiting marriage to a man and a woman is contrary to Canada's constitutional protections for all citizens, and is thus unconstitutional.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="33"><scu uid="39" label="Gay marriage has made headway in Canada" weight="4"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041203.0250"><line>Senator Maria Szyszkowska, a member of Prime Minister Marek Belka's Democratic Left Alliance who authored the bill, said the decision marks the &quot;start of building tolerance in Poland.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041001.0392"><line>&quot;The Church has nothing to say about it.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050407.0086"><line>None of what has been forecasted or what we've been warned about seems to have happened there.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041001.0392"><line>According to Justice Minister Juan Fernando Lopez de Aguilar, &quot;this initiative has not been taken against anything or anyone&quot; and he told the news conference that the government &quot;is cooperating with the (Roman Catholic) Church and considers that an open conflict with it is not good.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041001.0493"><line>&quot;The requirements on the various parties set out in resolution 1559 have not been met,&quot; said the report, obtained by AFP.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041103.0177"><line>&quot;Congress didn't really take this issue up this year in earnest and this sends a message to Washington that a lot of Americans feel strongly about this issue,&quot; she told AFP.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041109.0231"><line>The judge said the case &quot;isn't simply about tax bands.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041001.0392"><line>The interests of the Americans, English, Australian, French, Polish, Norwegian, South Korean and Japanese are everywhere,&quot; he said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041221.0313"><line>But it was not until a recently married local woman, Susie Kilpatrick, went to a regional Social Security office on Dec. 3 to legally take her husband's name that the new policy drew complaints.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041005.0163"><line>&quot;You know the old saying: Pigs get fat; hogs get slaughtered.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041221.0313"><line>&quot;We're delighted that this has been reversed,&quot; she said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041109.0231"><line>He conceded that the Irish Constitution drafted 67 years ago by then-Prime Minister Eamon de Valera undoubtedly presumed that &quot;marriage&quot; meant between a husband and wife, but argued that constitutional law should not be trapped within &quot;the permafrost of 1937.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041103.0177"><line>Supporters of legal bans on gay marriage were overjoyed that their stance had been so heavily endorsed across the country.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041001.0392"><line>The message focused particularly on countries supporting the US-led coalition in Iraq and pointed out that their interests were everywhere.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041005.0163"><line>&quot;Clearly the people knew what the amendment was intended to do and they agree with it,&quot; Johnson said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041203.0250"><line>&quot;This is the first, very difficult and very important step toward making this a normal country,&quot; Niemiec told Polish news agency PAP.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050407.0086"><line>&quot;Now we can wait to see who's right.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041109.0231"><line>&quot;Today is a happy day.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041005.0163"><line>While heterosexual relationships result in children, he said, &quot;You don't get the equivalent in a homosexual relationship.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050407.0086"><line>Ultimately, the dispute will be decided by the U.S. Supreme Court.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041001.0493"><line>The Spanish government Friday approved plans for homosexual marriage, including the right of gay couples to adopt, making the the country the most liberal in Europe, with Belgium and the Netherlands, in the field of gay rights.<annotation scu-count="3" sum-count="7" sums="10,11,14,23,30,41,49"><scu uid="48" label="Spain took steps to legalize homosexual marriages" weight="4"/><scu uid="51" label="The Netherlands and Belgium allow gay marriage" weight="2"/><scu uid="57" label="The right to adopt is not universally awarded to legal gay couples" weight="1"/></annotation></line><line>Gay couples have the same rights as heterosexual couples, in particular insofar as inheritance and succession rights are concerned, but do not have the right to adopt.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041001.0392"><line>Once the reform becomes law Spain will join the Netherlands and Belgium in allowing full homosexual marriage, though only the Netherlands allows gay couples to adopt.<annotation scu-count="3" sum-count="8" sums="10,12,3,35,40,42,43,44"><scu uid="48" label="Spain took steps to legalize homosexual marriages" weight="4"/><scu uid="51" label="The Netherlands and Belgium allow gay marriage" weight="2"/><scu uid="57" label="The right to adopt is not universally awarded to legal gay couples" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041109.0231"><line>High Court Justice Liam McKechnie said lawyers representing Ann Louise Gilligan and Katherine Zappone had presented an arguable case that merited a full hearing, likely to take place next year.</line><line>Their lead lawyer, Gerard Hogan, argued Monday that neither Ireland's 1937 constitution nor its more recent tax laws explicitly defines marriage as solely between a man and a woman.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="32,5"><scu uid="54" label="Some European countries have taken steps to allow gay marriages" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041203.0250"><line>Pope John Paul II, a native of Poland whose words carry great sway in this predominantly Catholic country, last month reiterated his outspoken opposition to gay marriage.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="36"><scu uid="44" label="The Roman Catholic Church opposes gay marriage" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041005.0163"><line>Morvant said the second ban was accomplished with this sentence: &quot;A legal status identical or substantially similar to that of marriage for unmarried individuals shall not be valid or recognized.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041103.0177"><line>But in other states, the public reception to such innovation was frosty.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041001.0392"><line>Zawahiri, the righthand man of Osama bin Laden, was last heard in a videotape broadcast by the Qatar-based news channel on September 9 in which he forecast a US defeat in Iraq and Afghanistan.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050407.0086"><line>Voters will decide the question in Alabama in June 2006, and in South Dakota and Tennessee at the 2006 election.</line><line>With conservatives pushing to define marriage as between a man and woman throughout the country, similar proposals are on the ballot in three other states next year and more than a dozen are considering them.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="43,55"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041103.0177"><line>&quot;These state amendments are a political dress rehearsal for the federal marriage amendment,&quot; the Alliance for Marriage's Daniels said.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041005.0163"><line>A judge on Tuesday threw out an amendment to the Louisiana Constitution banning gay marriage, a ruling applauded by civil-rights advocates but dismissed by social conservatives as a temporary hitch in their campaign to limit the legal rights of gay and lesbian couples.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="6" sums="11,13,21,23,29,30"><scu uid="45" label="In Louisiana a state ban on gay marriage was thrown out " weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041001.0392"><line>Some 14 articles of the civil code will be altered so that the words &quot;man and woman&quot; and &quot;father and mother&quot; are replaced by &quot;partners&quot; or &quot;parents&quot;.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050407.0086"><line>It shows to me there is a tremendous grass roots consensus that marriage is between a man and a woman.&quot;<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="43"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041109.0231"><line>Britain and Spain plan to follow suit soon.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041103.0177"><line>&quot;We have lost a battle but the process has begun of winning the war,&quot; said David Buckel, director of the marriage project at gay rights lobby group Lambda Legal, which vigorously opposed the amendments.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041203.0250"><line>If it becomes law, the bill would allow gay couples to register with city or town officials, which would give them inheritance rights and other legal guarantees _ but not the right to adopt children.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="33"><scu uid="57" label="The right to adopt is not universally awarded to legal gay couples" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041105.0605"><line>The Canadian government has been saying for more than a year that it wants to legalize same-sex marriage, but is awaiting a decision from the Canadian Supreme Court on the constitutionality of a draft law it has tabled on the question.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="20"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041109.0231"><line>He also cautioned that his ruling offered no indication as to whether the couple's complaint would be upheld or rejected, merely that it contained sufficient merit to be heard.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050314.0562"><line>San Francisco Superior Court Judge Richard Kramer ruled that a state law limiting marriage as an exclusive union between a man and a woman violated a constitutional right to equal treatment.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="20"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041103.0177"><line>Political observers had said that the emotional issue of legalising gay marriage -- along with other issues including abortion and stem cell research -- could mobilise conservative voters at the polls Tuesday, boosting the re-election prospects for Republican Bush.</line><line>But he said: &quot;This issue is going to be resolved by the US Supreme Court, and it's not going to give a damn what these state constitutions say.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041005.0163"><line>He described it as a minor setback.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="32"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050407.0086"><line>Bills are also moving forward in Minnesota, South Carolina and Texas to put the measure on the ballot there.</line><line>On Wednesday, the state Senate voted 27-9 to recognize civil unions; proponents say the bill will likely clear the House _ also controlled by the Democrats _ possibly as early as next week.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041001.0392"><line>It will also give gay couples the right to adopt.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="21,32"/></line><line>&quot;This law is part of the Socialist programme which has been voted for by the Spanish,&quot;said Beatriz Gimeno, president of the country's Gay, Lesbian and Transexuals Federation.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041221.0313"><line>But Social Security officials failed to differentiate between the village of New Paltz, where the homosexual weddings took place, and the larger town of New Paltz, which refuses to recognize same-sex marriages, and has the sole authority to issue legally binding marriage licenses.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="5"><scu uid="73" label="Parts of the US differ in whether or not they approve gay marriage" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041203.0250"><line>&quot;A long a hard road is still ahead of us, but the most important step has been taken.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041109.0231"><line>Legal observers say the Irish women's case, if successful here, could inspire similar lawsuits in the most conservative quarters of Europe, where gay couples are denied the rights of married heterosexual couples.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050407.0086"><line>But much of the rest of the country would likely back a ban, he said, predicting as many as 40 states would adopt them.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041005.0163"><line>We anticipated opposition at the pre-amendment level, and we overcame it there.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="32"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041221.0313"><line>Officials said that after getting a better understanding of the legal authority that local officials had to issue marriage licenses, they decided to overturn a policy that had been in effect for most of this year.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050407.0086"><line>&quot;When the people are given a chance to decide, their view is overwhelming,&quot; said Peter Sprigg at the conservative Family Research Council.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041001.0392"><line>&quot;Most Spanish people think what is important in adoption is the well-being of the child quite apart from the sexual orientation of the parents,&quot; she said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050407.0086"><line>It seems a can't-lose proposition: Ask voters to ban same-sex marriages and they consistently endorse the idea, from the South to the West.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="3" sums="0,2,41"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041105.0605"><line>Same-sex marriage is now allowed in more than half of Canada's 10 provinces and three territories.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041221.0313"><line>When her application was rejected, Kilpatrick and her husband, Jeremy Wilkening, sought help from their congressman, Rep. Maurice Hinchey.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041005.0163"><line>But opponents argued that without a constitutional amendment, gays could attempt to &quot;export&quot; marriages from other states to Louisiana.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="18"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050407.0086"><line>&quot;Courts are trying to take the decision out of the hands of the people.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041103.0177"><line>Ohio's amendment was the most sweeping, also banning any legal status &quot;that intends to approximate the design, qualities, significance or effect of marriage.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041005.0163"><line>Missouri voters approved an amendment banning same-sex marriage earlier this year.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="18"><scu uid="63" label="Missouri bans gay marriage" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041001.0392"><line>We should learn the lesson of Chechnya, Afghanistan, of Iraq, of Palestine.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041221.0313"><line>The village in Ulster County issued same-sex marriage affidavits to about 300 gay couples.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="43"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050407.0086"><line>Meanwhile, courts are continuing to hash out the dispute, giving hope to both sides.</line><line>&quot;People are going on with their lives, gay and lesbian couples are raising their families and living their lives like everyone else.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041203.0250"><line>&quot;If this bill was implemented it would bring irreparable social damage for marriage and family and upbringing of children,&quot; Kloch said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050407.0086"><line>In Maine, a new law signed last month protects gays and lesbians from discrimination, though it made clear it doesn't extend the rights of marriage.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="3" sums="25,43,44"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041005.0163"><line>Randy Evans, an attorney representing a Louisiana gay-rights group called Forum for Equality, predicted that Tuesday's decision would send civil-rights advocates in other states scrambling to see if they could bring legal challenges on similar grounds.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050407.0086"><line>&quot;The more places that we are able to extend the same rights and responsibilities to all Americans, the more places we've got a light to shine on what's happening,&quot; said Joe Solmonese, president of Human Rights Campaign, a gay rights lobbying group.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041109.0231"><line>Gilligan and Zappone _ who were married in British Columbia in September 2003 within months of the legalization of same-sex marriage there _ are the first gay couple in Ireland to go to court to seek state recognition of a foreign marriage.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="5" sums="22,3,35,37,6"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041005.0163"><line>District Judge William Morvant said that the Louisiana Legislature, which wrote the amendment this spring before voters overwhelmingly approved it in September, had failed to make it narrow enough.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041001.0392"><line>&quot;It's the era of Muslim resistance, after the (Arab) governments submitted to the Zionist occupant.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041109.0231"><line>The case, if successful, would have major implications for Ireland's unmarried couples, both heterosexual and homosexual, in this predominantly Catholic country of 3.9 million.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050407.0086"><line>New England states aren't the only ones to offer gay rights activists hope.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041005.0163"><line>It was added during legislative debate at the behest of lobbyists who wanted to go beyond a gay-marriage ban, said Evan Wolfson, executive director of Freedom to Marry, a nonprofit group that works nationwide for &quot;marriage equality.&quot;</line><line>&quot;The Christian Coalition got greedy,&quot; he said.</line><line>&quot;You get disease,&quot; Mills said.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041103.0177"><line>The measures, similar in structure across the nation, succeeded in Arkansas, Georgia, Kentucky, Michigan, Mississippi, Montana, North Dakota, Ohio, Oklahoma, Oregon and Utah.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041001.0392"><line>Spain's Socialist Prime Minister Jose Luis Rodriguez Zapatero, who took office in April, has made legalising gay marriages a key element of his social policy despite outrage from the Church.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="40"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041109.0231"><line>Under Irish law, married couples enjoy advantages over unmarried couples, who pay higher income and inheritance taxes.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041001.0493"><line>- NORTHERN EUROPE: Denmark was the first country in the world to authorise (on October 1, 1989) a &quot;registered partnership&quot; between gays.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050407.0086"><line>If the bill becomes law, Connecticut would be the only state to do so without a court order demanding lawmakers act.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041001.0493"><line>- FRANCE: In October 1999 the Civil Pact of Solidarity (PACS) giving legal status to non-married couples, in UNITED NATIONS, Oct 1 (AFP) - Lebanon and Syria have not met the demands in last month's UN Security Council resolution calling for the respect of Lebanese sovereignty, UN Secretary General Kofi Annan said in a new report on Friday.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041221.0313"><line>&quot;And we're sympathetic and hopeful that someday this will be extended to all couples that make the same lifelong commitments.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041001.0392"><line>The idea has been fiercely opposed by the Roman Catholic Church and a senior cleric earlier this week blasted the plans.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041005.0163"><line>And we think we will be successful in the end.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041001.0493"><line>- BELGIUM: Marriage between homosexuals became legal on June 1, 2003: since February it also covers foreigners.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041001.0392"><line>&quot;We must start the resistance from now... against the Crusader campaign... like resistance in Iraq, Afghanistan, in Palestine and in Chechnya,&quot; he said, taking aim in particular at the United States, Britain and France.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041103.0177"><line>The midwestern state of Missouri approved a constitutional ban on gay marriage by a huge margin in August, as did Louisiana in September.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041001.0392"><line>But according to an opinion poll conducted in late July, some two-thirds of Spaniards are in favour of gay marriages and now the cabinet has approved the bill such liaisons could become legal from as early as next year.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="40,43"/></line><line>&quot;We should start the resistance from now.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041109.0231"><line>The case is also a legal first for Europe, where Belgium and the Netherlands already allow same-sex marriages and several other nations grant homosexual couples similar tax, inheritance and child-rearing rights as husbands and wives have.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="3,35"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041221.0313"><line>Kilpatrick, 30, said she expected to try to change her name again next year.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050407.0086"><line>The New England examples _ most decisively Vermont's civil unions and Massachusetts' legalized gay marriages _ are seen by ban supporters as the threat that's helping their cause.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041005.0163"><line>Most if not all are expected to succeed.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041203.0250"><line>Poland's upper house of parliament approved a bill Friday that would allow gay couples to gain legal partnership rights, immediately drawing sharp criticism from the nation's powerful Roman Catholic Church.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="1" sums="51"><scu uid="49" label="Poland took steps toward approving legal partnerships" weight="2"/><scu uid="44" label="The Roman Catholic Church opposes gay marriage" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041005.0163"><line>Measures are on the November ballot in Arkansas, Georgia, Kentucky, Michigan, Mississippi, Montana, North Dakota, Ohio, Oklahoma, Oregon and Utah.</line><line>Michael Johnson, an attorney for the Alliance Defense Fund, a nonprofit group that opposes gay marriage, said Morvant's decision would be appealed.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041105.0605"><line>Same-sex marriage was first authorized in Canada in June 2003 by an Ontario court, followed by court decisions in the provinces of British Columbia, Quebec, Manitoba and Nova Scotia, and the Yukon Territory.</line><line>The government specifically wants a ruling on whether the draft law protects the right of churches to refuse to officiate in same-sex marriage.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041005.0163"><line>And, he said, it will &quot;give a boost to people around the country who are fighting these same amendments.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041103.0177"><line>&quot;Most of these states already had their legislatures write discrimination into the statutes, and now they have enshrined it in their constitutions,&quot; he told AFP.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041203.0250"><line>Szymon Niemiec, the head of Poland's Association of Gays and Lesbians said the upper house's decision was a &quot;huge success for Poland's democracy&quot; but acknowledged it would be an uphill struggle to get the bill passed into law.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050407.0086"><line>The northeastern New England states have been the major holdout; there, legislators and judges have strengthened rights for gays and lesbians.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="4" sums="0,2,48,57"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041109.0231"><line>&quot;Yesterday and today are simply the first steps to seek legal recognition of our lifelong love and faithfulness.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041203.0250"><line>But Father Jerzy Kloch, spokesman for the Polish Episcopate blasted the measure, saying it violates Poland's constitution, which says &quot;a marriage is a union between a man and a woman.&quot;<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="43"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041001.0392"><line>She said that about four million of Spain's 40 million inhabitants were homosexual.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050407.0086"><line>Kansas on Tuesday became the latest and 18th state to pass a constitutional amendment barring gay marriage.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="4" sums="29,30,37,6"><scu uid="70" label="Kansas bans gay marriage" weight="1"/></annotation></line><line>On the Net:</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041221.0313"><line>About 125 heterosexual couples have been married in New Paltz since February.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050407.0086"><line>A New York state judge ruled along similar lines in February.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041109.0231"><line>&quot;We have been exceptionally blessed by our unconditional love for, and fidelity to, one another,&quot; said Zappone, with her partner standing beside her.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041005.0163"><line>&quot;We anticipated opposition in the legislative process, and we overcame it there.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041103.0177"><line>The amendments generally passed with a 3-1 majority, except in Oregon where earlier returns showed it had succeeded by about 55 percent.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041203.0250"><line>He warned against attempts to tamper with what he called &quot;the irreplaceable&quot; institution of marriage-based family in an apparent reference to moves like granting homosexual couples social benefits.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041109.0231"><line>Zappone, a member of Ireland's government-appointed Human Rights Commission, and Gilligan, a Dublin philosophy lecturer, have been partners for 23 years and live together in Brittas, a beachside resort south of Dublin.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041005.0163"><line>And the public, he argued, would be forced to underwrite the costs of gay relationships, such as AIDS.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041109.0231"><line>A lesbian couple who wed in Canada can seek to have their union legally recognized in Ireland, a judge ruled Tuesday in a case he predicted would have deep consequences for this predominantly Catholic country.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="1" sums="14"><scu uid="39" label="Gay marriage has made headway in Canada" weight="4"/><scu uid="54" label="Some European countries have taken steps to allow gay marriages" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050407.0086"><line>New Hampshire set up a commission to study civil unions after legislators last year refused to recognize gay marriage.</line><line>And by then, years of gays and lesbians living as partners recognized by Massachusetts, Vermont and elsewhere will test the warnings of critics that gay marriage is a threat to the institution of marriage, he said.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="10"><scu uid="38" label="Massachusetts allows homosexual marriage" weight="4"/></annotation></line><line>Marriage is still there,&quot; he said.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="13"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041103.0177"><line>That would create a legal barrier to civil unions, as well as marriages for gay couples.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041001.0493"><line>Norway (1993), Sweden (1994), Iceland (1996) and Finland (2001) followed suit.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041103.0177"><line>Massachusetts legalized gay marriage in May while the eastern state of Vermont allows civil unions.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="5" sums="12,37,42,57,6"><scu uid="38" label="Massachusetts allows homosexual marriage" weight="4"/><scu uid="42" label="Vermont allows civil unions" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041109.0231"><line>The 2001 census identified 77,600 households involving unmarried partners, among them 1,300 homosexual couples.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041001.0392"><line>Such unions are also legal in six Canadian provinces and the northeastern US state of Massachusetts.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="1" sums="3"><scu uid="38" label="Massachusetts allows homosexual marriage" weight="4"/><scu uid="39" label="Gay marriage has made headway in Canada" weight="4"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041001.0493"><line>Sweden is the only one to authorise adoption (since February 2003).</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041103.0177"><line>The move to change state constitutions reflected a growing public debate on same-sex marriage after Massachusetts earlier this year became the first US state to sanction such unions.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041005.0163"><line>If that happened, Mills said, institutions such as churches and schools would be forced to accept homosexuality.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041103.0177"><line>&quot;But in many ways, these results also show that it's a state issue and that the states can deal with it themselves without federal government intervention,&quot; she said.</line><line>Voters in eleven US states voted overwhelmingly Tuesday to impose constitutional bans on gay marriage, one of the hottest issues in this year's presidential election, results showed.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="7" sums="19,25,29,30,48,51,55"/></line><line>&quot;We knew going into these amendment fights that we were going to take it on the chin in most places,&quot; said Matt Foreman, executive director of the National Gay and Lesbian Task Force.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041001.0392"><line>This interventionist tendency by the Church is the virus and must be eradicated,&quot;.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041103.0177"><line>The measure had been widely expected to pass in all 11 states where it featured on the ballot, said Jennie Drage Bowser, policy analyst with the National Conference of State Legislatures, which monitored state ballot initiatives.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041105.0605"><line>Canadian media said five homosexual couples had asked to be married in Saskatchewan.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041221.0313"><line>The town, which surrounds the village, has not issued marriage licenses to any gay couple.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="32"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041105.0605"><line>A court decision Friday made Saskatchewan the seventh Canadian province to authorize marriage between people of the same sex.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="23,49"><scu uid="39" label="Gay marriage has made headway in Canada" weight="4"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041005.0163"><line>&quot;This is the third quarter, late in the game,&quot; Mills said.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041001.0392"><line>The Spanish government on Friday approved a bill to legalise homosexual marriages, which will make it only the third country in Europe to condone same sex marriages.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="4" sums="19,33,35,48"><scu uid="48" label="Spain took steps to legalize homosexual marriages" weight="4"/><scu uid="54" label="Some European countries have taken steps to allow gay marriages" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050407.0086"><line>&quot;Every state that had this on the ballot passed it.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041109.0231"><line>They have worked together on poverty research and feminist rights projects since the early 1980s.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050407.0086"><line>The Connecticut Senate on Wednesday voted to legalize civil unions.</line><line>&quot;To be frank, every time one of those decisions comes down it just adds fuel to the fire for our efforts,&quot; Sprigg said.</line><line>A California state judge ruled last month that the state law banning gay marriage was unconstitutional and that gay couples can marry.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="10" sums="12,13,19,21,25,32,36,42,43,57"><scu uid="46" label="In California, a state ban on gay marriage was thrown out " weight="4"/><scu uid="73" label="Parts of the US differ in whether or not they approve gay marriage" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041001.0392"><line>The US intelligence agency, the CIA, said then it believed that tape to be authentic and could have been recently recorded.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041203.0250"><line>The senate voted 38-23 with 15 abstentions to send the draft to the lower house, or Sejm, where the bill was expected to meet resistance.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041001.0392"><line>&quot;Don't wait for the American, British, French, South Korean, Hungarian and Polish forces to enter Egypt, the Arabian Peninsula, Yemen and Algeria to start the resistance,&quot; the speaker added.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050407.0086"><line>Connecticut offers the strongest recent pro-gay legislation, by extending all rights and privileges of marriage to same-sex couples but without an actual marriage license.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041001.0392"><line>&quot;All (these countries) participated in the occupation of Afghanistan or Iraq or Chechnya, or help Israel to survive,&quot; added the voice.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050407.0086"><line>Advocates for gay marriage also see those examples as a plus, by proving that fears gay marriage will somehow destroy society's social fabric are unfounded.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="21"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041005.0163"><line>This one, Morvant ruled, had two: The first was to ban gay marriage; the second was to ban civil unions and domestic partnerships.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050407.0086"><line>For ban supporters, the key difference is a vote of the people.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041001.0493"><line>In all these countries the law gives gay couples the same legal and social rights as married heterosexual couples.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="4" sums="37,48,49,6"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050314.0562"><line>A US judge on Monday ruled that a California state law that effectively bans gay marriage is unconstitutional, a clerk of the court told AFP.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="10" sums="11,20,22,25,30,36,41,44,49,51"><scu uid="46" label="In California, a state ban on gay marriage was thrown out " weight="4"/><scu uid="73" label="Parts of the US differ in whether or not they approve gay marriage" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041109.0231"><line>Zappone and Gilligan are demanding that Ireland's tax collection agency, the Revenue Commissioners, allow them to file as a married couple rather than as two single people, which involves paying more tax.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041221.0313"><line>Hinchey, a Democrat, wrote a letter urging the Social Security commissioner to recognize that the policy was arbitrary and overreaching.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041103.0177"><line>Gay activists were angry but unsurprised at the development and vowed that the fight for legal equality for homosexual was far from over.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041005.0163"><line>Nearly 78 percent of voters in Louisiana supported the amendment, one of 13 similar measures states are weighing this fall.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050407.0086"><line>&quot;Now we have laboratories to observe whether these predictions would come true,&quot; Eskridge said.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041005.0163"><line>According to state law, constitutional amendments are valid only if they have a single legal purpose.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050407.0086"><line>Republican Gov. M. Jodi Rell has not taken a stand on the bill, but has said she supports the concept of civil unions.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041103.0177"><line>The politically and socially divisive issue drove a wedge between civil rights lobbyists and conservative Christians earlier this year, climaxing in a failed bid, backed by President George W. Bush, to pass a federal constitutional amendment banning the practice.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050407.0086"><line>&quot;Massachusetts, the last time I checked... is still there.</line><line>Both decisions are under appeal.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041005.0163"><line>That phrasing was not contained in early drafts of the amendment.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041001.0493"><line>In January Danish Prime Minister Anders Fogh Rasmussen backed a religious ceremony for gay couples.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041001.0392"><line>&quot;Young Muslims, here is our message... if we are killed or taken prisoner, continue the path (of resistance) after us. Don't betray God and his Prophet,&quot; said the voice attributed to be Zawahiri's.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041103.0177"><line>Returns showed that all 11 state referenda on constitutional amendments that define marriage as being exclusively between a man and a woman had passed across the nation.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="3" sums="13,29,55"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041001.0392"><line>De la Vega said: &quot;There are thousands of children already living in Spain with homosexual parents and more than 50 studies show there are no differences between children who grow up with homosexual parents and others.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041203.0250"><line>&quot;The church has made its stand on the issue known many times during meetings between the church and the government and we hope such law will not be implemented in Poland.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041001.0392"><line>&quot;It would impose on society a virus, something false, which will have negative consequences for social life,&quot; insisted Juan Antonio Martinez Camino, spokesman for Spain's Episcopal Conference.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041109.0231"><line>He noted that in a country where homosexuality itself was outlawed until 1993, any move to accord gay couples the same legal rights as husbands and wives would have &quot;profound ethical, cultural and religious&quot; ramifications.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041221.0313"><line>Until the reversal, the agency had refused to accept as identification any marriage document issued in New Paltz since February, when an official gained national attention by performing same-sex marriages.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041001.0493"><line>- NETHERLANDS: The Dutch Senate adopted in December 2000 legislation authorising civil homosexual marriage and the adoption by two same-sex parents of children provided the children have Dutch nationality.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041001.0392"><line>The plan &quot;recognises all rights for homosexuals, when it comes to qualifying for a pension, administering an estate, asking for a loan, authorising surgery for a partner,&quot; cabinet spokeswoman Maria Teresa Fernandez de la Vega told reporters.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041221.0313"><line>The Social Security Administration reversed itself late Monday and said that it would recognize marriage licenses issued for heterosexual couples by the clerk of the town of New Paltz, N.Y.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="14"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041109.0231"><line>Hogan, one of Ireland's most prominent experts on constitutional law, said the Revenue Commissioners &quot;have discriminated against them in an unjust and invidious manner, in breach of their constitutional rights and the European Convention on Human Rights.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050407.0086"><line>Yale law Professor William Eskridge, a constitutional scholar active in support of gay rights issues, said that, in the end, New England won't be the lone holdout, and expects resistance to the bans across the Northeast and the West Coast.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041103.0177"><line>&quot;It's a democratic tidal wave for marriage,&quot; said Matt Daniels, president of the Alliance for Marriage, one of the groups that pushed for the bans.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041001.0392"><line>Spain &quot;is in the forefront of Europe and of the world in the struggle against centuries of discrimination,&quot; de la Vega said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041203.0250"><line>This is a huge change.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041001.0493"><line>Homosexual couples have the same rights as heterosexual partners, except in the areas of insemination and adoption.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041001.0392"><line>&quot;But also when it comes to asking to adopt a child.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041001.0493"><line>For the union to be valid one of the partners needs to be Belgian or to live in Belgium.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041005.0163"><line>We've got to play a whole other quarter of ball.</line><line>Gene Mills, executive director of the Louisiana Family Forum, another group fighting to ban gay marriage, said that he &quot;fundamentally disagreed&quot; with the judge's decision.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050407.0086"><line>The state already allows for domestic partners, who could be homosexual or heterosexual, to have many of the legal rights of marriage, such as rights to inheritance and benefits.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041221.0313"><line>In a statement released by his office in Washington, Hinchey, on his way back from Ukraine, said the Social Security Administration should also overturn similar policies that remain in effect in Asbury Park, N.J., and in other places around the country that have permitted gay marriage ceremonies.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041005.0163"><line>Gay-rights supporters had argued that the amendment was unnecessary since Louisiana already had a law banning gay marriage.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="8" sums="19,22,36,37,44,51,57,6"/></line></document></collection>